An inquiry into 'third way' economic schools that are neither individualist-capitalist nor socialist-collectivist, but based on the human person, solidarity communities and self-organization, and are civil society or commons centric. We are thinking of movements such as distributism, solidarism, associationism, social credit, mutualism, etc .. This could be seen as a search for antecedents to construct a commons-oriented economics and societal form.